05780nam a22009975i 9780520938564DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20052005cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209385647 a10.1525/97805209385642doi  a(DE-B1597)520798  a(OCoLC)1110708313  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aF2520.1.Y3bB67 2005eb 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a306.089981 aBorofsky, Rob, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aYanomami :bThe Fierce Controversy and What We Can Learn from It /cRob Borofsky. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (391 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCalifornia Series in Public Anthropology ;v1200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note To Teachers -- tA Personal Note To Undergraduates -- tSuggested Yanomami / Yanomamö Films -- tHelping The Yanomami -- tPart I -- t1. The Controversy And The Broader Issues At Stake -- t2. Chagnon And Tierney In Their Own Words -- t3. How The Controversy Has Played Out In American Anthropology -- t4. Broader Issues At Stake In The Controversy -- t5. Keeping Yanomami Perspectives In Mind -- t6. You Decide -- t7. A Platform For Change -- tPart II -- t8. Round One -- t9. Round Two -- t10. Round Three -- t11. Three Assessments -- tAppendix: Summary Of The Roundtable Participants’ Positions -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aYanomami raises questions central to the field of anthropology—questions concerning the practice of fieldwork, the production of knowledge, and anthropology's intellectual and ethical vision of itself. Using the Yanomami controversy—one of anthropology's most famous and explosive imbroglios—as its starting point, this book draws readers into not only reflecting on but refashioning the very heart and soul of the discipline. It is both the most up-to-date and thorough public discussion of the Yanomami controversy available and an innovative and searching assessment of the current state of anthropology. The Yanomami controversy came to public attention through the publication of Patrick Tierney's best-selling book, Darkness in El Dorado, in which he accuses James Neel, a prominent geneticist who belonged to the National Academy of Sciences, as well as Napoleon Chagnon, whose introductory text on the Yanomami is perhaps the best-selling anthropological monograph of all time, of serious human rights violations. This book identifies the ethical dilemmas of the controversy and raises deeper, structural questions about the discipline. A portion of the book is devoted to a unique roundtable in which important scholars on different sides of the issues debate back and forth with each other. This format draws readers into deciding, for themselves, where they stand on the controversy’s—and many of anthropology’s—central concerns. All of the royalties from this book will be donated to helping the Yanomami improve their healthcare.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAnthropological ethicsxStudy and teaching (Higher). 0aAnthropologistsxProfessional relationships. 0aAnthropologyxAuthorship. 0aAnthropologyxFieldwork. 0aAnthropology. 0aSocial history. 0aYanomamo IndiansxAttitudes. 0aYanomamo IndiansxPublic opinion. 0aYanomamo IndiansxSocial conditions. 0aYanomamo IndiansxStudy and teaching (Higher). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aacademic concerns.  aacademic disciplines.  aanthropologists.  aanthropology.  acontroversial.  acritical questions.  aculture and society.  ael dorado.  aethical dilemmas.  aethical practices.  aethics of anthropology.  afieldwork.  ahea